1
00:02:27,482 --> 00:02:30,280
<i>- S. Bueno.
- Family is everything.</i>

2
00:02:30,385 --> 00:02:32,182
<i>No?</i>

3
00:02:32,287 --> 00:02:35,688
<i>Now, do you love your son?</i>

4
00:02:36,658 --> 00:02:40,424
S.

5
00:02:47,302 --> 00:02:51,898
<i>Now... do you understand?</i>

6
00:02:52,006 --> 00:02:56,375
<i>You have a $10 million insurance policy.
I know that.</i>

7
00:05:05,874 --> 00:05:08,001
Georgina!

8
00:05:08,109 --> 00:05:11,374
Obey me, I will love you.
Come on.

9
00:05:11,479 --> 00:05:13,242
That's how it works, huh?

10
00:05:13,348 --> 00:05:16,511
<i>- Simple.
- That's right.</i>

11
00:05:16,618 --> 00:05:18,518
Mwah.

12
00:05:22,657 --> 00:05:25,956
She got a sister?

13
00:05:26,060 --> 00:05:29,257
How's business?

14
00:05:29,364 --> 00:05:32,265
The Japanese are here in a big way.

15
00:05:33,701 --> 00:05:36,192
Cheap labor, factory space.

16
00:05:36,304 --> 00:05:40,263
But they feel a lot safer living
over the border in El Paso.

17
00:05:40,375 --> 00:05:43,435
I ferry them back and forth.
They think I'm John Wayne.

18
00:05:43,545 --> 00:05:45,445
- Ah.
- Come on.

19
00:05:49,918 --> 00:05:53,149
- I live like a king down here.
- Yes, you do.

20
00:05:56,891 --> 00:06:00,054
- You been workin'?
- Yeah. No.

21
00:06:00,161 --> 00:06:02,220
Nah. Been movin' around,
you know.

22
00:06:02,330 --> 00:06:06,391
Colombia, couple of places I can't name.
Nothing catches my fancy.

23
00:06:08,269 --> 00:06:11,238
Oh.

24
00:06:11,339 --> 00:06:13,899
You think God will forgive us
for what we've done?

25
00:06:14,008 --> 00:06:16,568
- No.
- You don't?

26
00:06:16,678 --> 00:06:20,842
Me either.

27
00:06:20,949 --> 00:06:25,750
- How long you staying?
- I don't know. I just... you know.

28
00:06:25,853 --> 00:06:29,812
I wanted to see you, Ray,
see how you're doin'.

29
00:06:29,924 --> 00:06:32,449
You know, I came by on impulse.

30
00:06:32,560 --> 00:06:36,121
Well, I could do with some impulse.

31
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:49,266
What happened?

32
00:06:49,377 --> 00:06:51,572
Family paid the ransom...

33
00:06:51,679 --> 00:06:55,672
then they sent the kid home
after a couple of days...

34
00:06:55,783 --> 00:06:57,944
minus an ear, of course.

35
00:06:58,052 --> 00:07:01,681
Now every mother in Mexico City with a little
bit of money wants bigger and better bodyguards...

36
00:07:01,789 --> 00:07:03,757
my own wife included.

37
00:07:03,858 --> 00:07:07,157
I hate to break it to you,
but she's right. She's right.

38
00:07:08,863 --> 00:07:13,129
Look, Sammy, all my clients have, uh,
kidnap and ransom insurance.

39
00:07:13,234 --> 00:07:16,465
I have a policy. A.I.G.
My dad gave it to me.

40
00:07:16,571 --> 00:07:19,836
Yeah, I know.
I got it for your dad.

41
00:07:19,941 --> 00:07:22,876
<i>But what are you gonna do in 60 days
when you can't renew it?</i>

42
00:07:22,977 --> 00:07:27,243
- You can't because you don't have a bodyguard.
- I had to let Emilio go.

43
00:07:27,348 --> 00:07:30,977
You gotta please Lisa.
I mean, hey, ass like that's hard to find.

44
00:07:33,421 --> 00:07:37,687
Look, a bodyguard's
like anything else.

45
00:07:37,792 --> 00:07:41,057
You get what you pay for, okay?

46
00:07:41,162 --> 00:07:44,154
You could do this.
You get one that's got a decent rsum.

47
00:07:44,265 --> 00:07:46,597
We're not looking for
goddamn Superman here, right?

48
00:07:46,701 --> 00:07:49,431
Get someone cheap
till you renew the policy...

49
00:07:49,537 --> 00:07:52,904
and then, uh...
then fire the prick for whatever.

50
00:07:53,007 --> 00:07:55,066
Incompetence.

51
00:07:55,176 --> 00:07:59,579
All kidding aside, the most important thing
is that your daughter goes back to school...

52
00:07:59,681 --> 00:08:02,650
and that your wife gets to save face.

53
00:08:02,750 --> 00:08:07,551
This way, you won't be the only
unprotected family in the neighborhood.

54
00:08:20,168 --> 00:08:23,365
<i>That's right. A bodyguard.
Your Spanish is good enough.</i>

55
00:08:23,471 --> 00:08:26,872
- You're crazy.
- You even look the part.

56
00:08:26,974 --> 00:08:29,442
In my state,
I couldn't guard a corpse.

57
00:08:29,544 --> 00:08:32,342
<i>It's rich guys flashing their cash.
It's all for show.</i>

58
00:08:32,447 --> 00:08:37,578
<i>- Nothing's gonna happen. - Yeah? You
think they'd hire a drunk, a has-been?</i>

59
00:08:39,253 --> 00:08:42,552
You have to keep it under control.

60
00:08:42,657 --> 00:08:47,424
What if there was, you know, say,
a kidnapping attempt? What do I do then?

61
00:08:47,528 --> 00:08:51,555
<i>You do your best. They're not gonna be
paying you enough to perform miracles.</i>

62
00:08:51,666 --> 00:08:54,260
<i>- I don't know.
- It's not exactly a scam, Crease.</i>

63
00:08:54,368 --> 00:08:58,600
- Even at half speed, you're pretty damn good.
- Yeah.

64
00:08:58,706 --> 00:09:00,901
Bodyguard's gotta be close
to people though.

65
00:09:01,008 --> 00:09:03,841
He gotta talk all the time,
and I'm no good at that.

66
00:09:03,945 --> 00:09:07,472
You'll be the silent type.
People are gonna appreciate that.

67
00:09:14,422 --> 00:09:17,289
Bodyguard. So who's the guy?

68
00:09:17,391 --> 00:09:20,292
Samuel Ramos. He's a young guy.

69
00:09:20,394 --> 00:09:23,192
<i>He owns one of the plants in Jurez.</i>

70
00:09:23,297 --> 00:09:25,231
<i>Yeah?</i>

71
00:09:25,333 --> 00:09:28,131
The Jap car industry is in the toilet.

72
00:09:28,236 --> 00:09:31,171
He's trying to persuade Ford
to partner with him.

73
00:09:31,272 --> 00:09:35,140
I think he's in trouble.
His family lives in Mexico City.

74
00:09:35,243 --> 00:09:37,768
He asked me if I knew
anybody he could trust.

75
00:09:39,347 --> 00:09:42,339
- And you thought of me.
- Yeah.

76
00:09:42,450 --> 00:09:45,851
Take a job, Crease.
Breathe some air.

77
00:09:45,953 --> 00:09:48,319
<i>Then decide if you want
to stick around or not.</i>

78
00:09:48,422 --> 00:09:52,518
<i>Besides, I'm glad to see you.
I got nobody to talk to down here.</i>

79
00:10:00,001 --> 00:10:02,902
Listen, my wife wants someone
presentable and polite.

80
00:10:05,273 --> 00:10:08,800
You'll be the fifth candidate
she sees this week.

81
00:10:08,910 --> 00:10:10,639
Your rsum's quite impressive.

82
00:10:10,745 --> 00:10:15,205
<i>Sixteen years of military experience,
extensive counterterrorism work.</i>

83
00:10:15,316 --> 00:10:18,877
I'm surprised anybody could afford you.
What's the catch?

84
00:10:18,986 --> 00:10:21,250
I drink.

85
00:10:21,355 --> 00:10:23,346
How does that affect you?

86
00:10:23,457 --> 00:10:25,925
Well...

87
00:10:26,027 --> 00:10:28,154
coordination, reaction time.

88
00:10:28,262 --> 00:10:32,028
If top professionals try to kidnap
your daughter, I'll do the best I can...

89
00:10:32,133 --> 00:10:35,159
but the service will be
on par with the pay.

90
00:10:36,304 --> 00:10:38,329
What if amateurs tried?

91
00:10:38,439 --> 00:10:41,567
I'd probably kill 'em.
Is that likely?

92
00:10:41,676 --> 00:10:43,644
No.

93
00:10:43,744 --> 00:10:46,508
No one is to know about your drinking.
That includes my wife.

94
00:11:13,407 --> 00:11:16,171
<i>Lisa!</i>

95
00:11:18,379 --> 00:11:20,279
Lisa!

96
00:11:31,492 --> 00:11:34,393
My wife, Lisa.
And this is John Creasy.

97
00:11:41,435 --> 00:11:43,665
- You're an American.
- So are you.

98
00:11:45,706 --> 00:11:47,503
It's all in there.

99
00:11:50,544 --> 00:11:52,478
Would you like a drink?

100
00:11:52,580 --> 00:11:55,310
Yes, uh, Jack and water'd be good.

101
00:11:56,884 --> 00:12:00,411
<i>- Have you done much of this kind of work before?
- No, ma'am.</i>

102
00:12:00,521 --> 00:12:04,287
But he has a lot of experience
in related fields.

103
00:12:06,794 --> 00:12:09,490
- You have a family, Mr. Creasy?
- No.

104
00:12:09,597 --> 00:12:11,792
Pita.

105
00:12:11,899 --> 00:12:13,867
<i>Pita.</i>

106
00:12:15,202 --> 00:12:17,295
<i>- Thank you.
- Yes, Mom?</i>

107
00:12:17,405 --> 00:12:19,305
Honey, this is, uh, Mr. Creasy.

108
00:12:24,478 --> 00:12:26,946
In English, honey.

109
00:12:27,048 --> 00:12:29,676
Um, do you wanna show
Mr. Creasy to his room?

110
00:12:29,784 --> 00:12:33,481
- This way, Mr. Creasy.
- Okay.

111
00:12:41,495 --> 00:12:43,895
Thank you.

112
00:12:50,838 --> 00:12:53,636
Just like that?

113
00:12:53,741 --> 00:12:56,141
I think it's nice...

114
00:12:56,243 --> 00:12:58,711
that he's an American.

115
00:12:58,813 --> 00:13:03,011
I think it's terrific. You sure?

116
00:13:05,686 --> 00:13:07,984
Thank you.

117
00:13:08,089 --> 00:13:10,717
Thank you.

118
00:13:10,825 --> 00:13:13,293
I feel better now.

119
00:13:15,196 --> 00:13:18,097
<i>- Hola, Bruno!
- Buenas tardes!</i>

120
00:13:18,199 --> 00:13:20,497
That's Bruno, the gardener.

121
00:13:20,601 --> 00:13:22,660
And, um, that's Maria, the cook.

122
00:13:22,770 --> 00:13:25,568
<i>- Hola, Maria!
- Hola, Pita.</i>

123
00:13:27,842 --> 00:13:31,869
We fixed the room up two weeks ago.
It's nicer than before.

124
00:13:35,049 --> 00:13:38,883
<i>You've got a TV and C.D. Player.
What kind of music do you like, Mr. Creasy?</i>

125
00:13:38,986 --> 00:13:41,352
I don't know.

126
00:13:41,455 --> 00:13:43,946
- You don't know?
- I don't know.

127
00:13:44,058 --> 00:13:47,221
That's Bird.

128
00:13:47,328 --> 00:13:50,195
Emilio forgot to take him
when he left.

129
00:13:51,365 --> 00:13:53,697
Emilio was my last bodyguard.

130
00:13:55,703 --> 00:13:59,935
Have you protected a lot of children
before, Mr. Creasy?

131
00:14:00,041 --> 00:14:02,805
Creasy. You can call me Creasy.
And no, you're the first.

132
00:14:02,910 --> 00:14:04,810
Creasy.

133
00:14:04,912 --> 00:14:06,846
Bye, Creasy.

134
00:14:06,947 --> 00:14:09,609
So long.

135
00:14:10,718 --> 00:14:12,447
Bye, Bird.

136
00:14:17,124 --> 00:14:19,456
Ow.

137
00:14:22,430 --> 00:14:25,922
- School tomorrow, peeps.
- Does that mean we can get a dog?

138
00:14:27,334 --> 00:14:29,802
<i>Dad promised me one
when I went back to school.</i>

139
00:14:29,904 --> 00:14:31,599
Yeah, we'll see.

140
00:14:31,705 --> 00:14:35,505
If you get a dog,
will you give up your bear?

141
00:14:35,609 --> 00:14:38,942
You're getting too old for him.

142
00:14:39,046 --> 00:14:42,447
<i>- How'd you like Mr. Creasy?
- Creasy.</i>

143
00:14:42,550 --> 00:14:44,916
He said to call him just Creasy.

144
00:14:45,019 --> 00:14:47,487
- Uh-huh.
- That isn't disrespectful, is it?

145
00:14:47,588 --> 00:14:49,886
No, not if he asked you.

146
00:14:49,990 --> 00:14:52,823
Here. There you go.

147
00:15:00,668 --> 00:15:04,468
- He's like a bear too.
- Yeah?

148
00:15:04,572 --> 00:15:06,870
A big, sad bear.

149
00:15:08,509 --> 00:15:12,138
- Is he sad?
- I think. Or something.

150
00:15:15,950 --> 00:15:17,850
- Good night, honey.
- Night.

151
00:15:21,288 --> 00:15:24,553
- Oh, can you get me some floss in the morning?
- Floss?

152
00:15:24,658 --> 00:15:28,185
- Yeah, the strawberry kind.
- Oh, sure.

153
00:15:30,531 --> 00:15:32,556
Good night, Bear.

154
00:15:33,667 --> 00:15:35,635
Creasy Bear.

155
00:16:09,170 --> 00:16:11,502
What's that one for?

156
00:16:11,605 --> 00:16:13,505
<i>La Virgin de Guadalupe.</i>

157
00:16:13,607 --> 00:16:18,010
Business. For Toyota, for Ford.

158
00:16:18,112 --> 00:16:20,740
If one dies, maybe she can
resurrect the other one.

159
00:16:20,848 --> 00:16:23,408
I don't know.

160
00:16:23,517 --> 00:16:26,452
She likes him.

161
00:16:28,155 --> 00:16:31,352
- What are you talking about?
- Creasy.

162
00:16:32,893 --> 00:16:35,555
Pita likes him.

163
00:16:35,663 --> 00:16:37,563
Pita loves school.

164
00:16:37,665 --> 00:16:42,864
<i>Pita would love Count Dracula
if he took her back there, honey.</i>

165
00:16:42,970 --> 00:16:44,938
Okay?

166
00:16:47,408 --> 00:16:50,275
<i>- Hey. Are you okay?
- I don't know.</i>

167
00:16:50,377 --> 00:16:54,473
Okay?

168
00:16:54,582 --> 00:16:57,016
I don't know, Lisa.

169
00:16:57,117 --> 00:16:59,085
I'm trying.

170
00:17:54,275 --> 00:17:56,243
Come on, Bird.

171
00:17:56,343 --> 00:17:59,710
That's right.
That's right. Come on.

172
00:17:59,813 --> 00:18:02,976
All right. Home to Emilio.

173
00:18:03,083 --> 00:18:05,950
You're home free, baby.

174
00:18:26,073 --> 00:18:28,837
- Where are you from, Creasy?
- The U.S.

175
00:18:28,942 --> 00:18:31,877
<i>- I know, but which state?
- No state in particular.</i>

176
00:18:31,979 --> 00:18:33,970
You can drive and talk
at the same time.

177
00:18:34,081 --> 00:18:36,549
No, I can't, Pita, so, please,
let me just do my job.

178
00:18:39,853 --> 00:18:42,720
Are you going to stay?

179
00:18:42,823 --> 00:18:44,723
My last bodyguard left.

180
00:18:44,825 --> 00:18:47,692
Somebody gave him
more money than we could.

181
00:18:47,795 --> 00:18:51,754
I guess that makes me
a bargain then, huh?

182
00:18:51,865 --> 00:18:56,268
Being black... is that a positive or negative
for a bodyguard in Mexico?

183
00:18:56,370 --> 00:18:58,270
Time will tell.

184
00:19:01,809 --> 00:19:06,041
There were 24 kidnappings
in Mexico City in the last six days.

185
00:19:06,146 --> 00:19:08,046
- Four a day.
- Yeah?

186
00:19:08,148 --> 00:19:10,616
- Twenty-four? - Twenty-four. What
do you think about that, Creasy?

187
00:19:10,718 --> 00:19:14,381
- I think that you know entirely more than you should.
- Well, thank you.

188
00:19:37,511 --> 00:19:40,139
<i>Hola, Miguel.</i>

189
00:19:42,683 --> 00:19:44,548
- See you later.
- You have to sign.

190
00:19:44,651 --> 00:19:48,951
- What?
- You have to sign in, show them your I.D.

191
00:19:49,056 --> 00:19:52,492
<i>Buenos das. Come on.</i>

192
00:19:53,660 --> 00:19:55,560
Right there.

193
00:19:55,662 --> 00:19:58,290
<i>- Hola, Manuel.
- Hola, Pita.</i>

194
00:20:09,076 --> 00:20:10,976
<i>- Hola, Pita!
- Hola!</i>

195
00:20:11,078 --> 00:20:15,276
Pita! It's so good to have you back.

196
00:20:15,382 --> 00:20:18,283
Sister Anna, this is
my new bodyguard, Creasy.

197
00:20:18,385 --> 00:20:21,513
Sister Anna, the headmistress.

198
00:20:21,622 --> 00:20:23,647
<i>Seor Creasy.</i>

199
00:20:23,757 --> 00:20:25,657
Hurry. Class is about to begin.

200
00:20:25,759 --> 00:20:28,091
- Go, go.
- Bye, Creasy.

201
00:20:28,195 --> 00:20:30,686
<i>- Madre.
- You must look after our Pita.</i>

202
00:20:30,798 --> 00:20:32,993
It is not good that she's late today.

203
00:20:33,100 --> 00:20:37,662
I'm very sorry. I, uh... I'll have to get
used to the rules. It won't happen again.

204
00:20:37,771 --> 00:20:41,332
No offense, but I regret
that your profession needs to exist.

205
00:20:41,442 --> 00:20:44,570
<i>So do I, Madre. So do I.</i>

206
00:20:44,678 --> 00:20:48,637
Do you ever see the hand of God
in what you do?

207
00:20:50,250 --> 00:20:52,377
No, not for a long time.

208
00:20:52,486 --> 00:20:55,853
The Bible says,
"Be not overcome of evil, but overcome... "

209
00:20:55,956 --> 00:20:59,392
"Overcome evil with good. "

210
00:21:05,532 --> 00:21:08,330
<i>I'm the sheep that got lost, Madre.</i>

211
00:22:11,732 --> 00:22:14,792
When you were a kid, Creasy,
did you like school?

212
00:22:16,370 --> 00:22:18,565
- I don't remember.
- You don't remember?

213
00:22:18,672 --> 00:22:22,574
No, I don't remember.
It, uh... Nah, I didn't like it.

214
00:22:22,676 --> 00:22:24,735
Why not?

215
00:22:24,845 --> 00:22:27,405
Because it wasn't a school like yours.

216
00:22:27,514 --> 00:22:29,482
There was no, uh... no Sister Anna.

217
00:22:32,386 --> 00:22:34,513
Were you unhappy?

218
00:22:36,723 --> 00:22:40,124
Being unhappy, Pita, that's a state of mind.
I really don't remember.

219
00:22:49,570 --> 00:22:51,663
What happened to your hand?

220
00:22:53,206 --> 00:22:55,106
- It's a birth defect.
- No, it's not.

221
00:22:55,208 --> 00:22:59,474
Look, no more questions, okay?

222
00:22:59,580 --> 00:23:01,946
- It really wasn't a question.
- It sounded like a question.

223
00:23:02,049 --> 00:23:04,643
<i>Look, I got a job to do. Hey!</i>

224
00:23:04,751 --> 00:23:06,981
<i>No. Gracias. Gracias. No. No.</i>

225
00:23:07,087 --> 00:23:10,022
Listen to me.
I'm being paid to protect you, okay?

226
00:23:10,123 --> 00:23:13,092
No, no, no. I'm being paid
to be your bodyguard.

227
00:23:13,193 --> 00:23:16,287
<i>Look at me.
I'm not being paid to be your friend.</i>

228
00:23:16,396 --> 00:23:19,957
<i>I'm being paid to protect you,
so no more questions. That's it. Period.</i>

229
00:23:23,770 --> 00:23:26,466
<i>- You hear me?
- Yes.</i>

230
00:23:26,573 --> 00:23:30,009
- And no crying.
- I'm not crying.

231
00:23:30,110 --> 00:23:33,170
Well, don't start.

232
00:23:33,280 --> 00:23:35,714
You gotta understand, this is a job.

233
00:23:35,816 --> 00:23:38,614
In order for me to do...

234
00:23:38,719 --> 00:23:40,653
In order for... Wait a minute.

235
00:24:30,303 --> 00:24:32,271
Yeah, come in.

236
00:24:37,878 --> 00:24:40,039
Mr. Creasy.

237
00:24:40,147 --> 00:24:42,945
I just wanted to make sure
you have everything you need.

238
00:24:43,050 --> 00:24:45,018
